{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a combinatorial optimization task involving graph embedding (topological map) onto a grid. To solve it, we must first understand the constraints of the input graph (colors and adjacencies) and then find the most compact layout to maximize empty cells.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "analyze_graph_topology",
      "instructions": "Parse the input city map to identify the set of colors (nodes) and their adjacency requirements (edges). Determine if the graph is a simple path, a tree, a cycle, or a complex graph with high-degree nodes. Calculate the minimum number of cells required to satisfy all adjacencies (the 'packing density' limit)."
    },
    {
      "label": "evaluate_connectivity_constraints",
      "instructions": "Identify any specific connectivity constraints (e.g., if certain colors must be connected via a specific path or if certain regions must remain separated). Check if the graph contains any 'bottleneck' nodes that dictate the minimum width or height of the required grid area."
    },
    {
      "label": "test_compact_packing_strategies",
      "instructions": "Simulate three specific layout strategies on a 50x50 grid: 1) Snake-like path packing (for path/tree graphs), 2) Spiral packing (for dense/cycle graphs), and 3) Cluster-based packing (grouping high-degree nodes in the center). For each strategy, calculate the number of cells used (N) and the resulting empty space E = 2500 - N."
    },
    {
      "label": "verify_grid_feasibility",
      "instructions": "For the best strategy found, verify that no two non-adjacent colors are placed in adjacent cells (if the problem implies strict adjacency preservation) and that the layout fits within the 50x50 boundary without violating the connectivity of the original map."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent will take the graph topology (helper 1) and constraints (helper 2) to select the most appropriate packing strategy. It will then use the results from the strategy simulations (helper 3) to identify the maximum E. Finally, it will use the verification (helper 4) to ensure the solution is valid and output the final score E + 1."
}
```

